  "prompt": "What is the main function of the rough endoplasmic reticulum?",
  "response": "The main function of the rough endoplasmic reticulum (RER) is protein synthesis and protein modification. It is called \"rough\" because it is studded with ribosomes on its surface, which give it a rough appearance under a microscope. These ribosomes are responsible for producing proteins that will be either secreted from the cell or inserted into cellular membranes. \n\nSpecifically, the rough endoplasmic reticulum:\n1. Translates messenger RNA into proteins\n2. Adds sugars to proteins (glycosylation)\n3. Folds proteins into their correct three-dimensional structure\n4. Helps prepare proteins for secretion or insertion into cell membranes\n5. Assists in quality control by identifying and marking misfolded proteins for destruction\n\nCells with high protein secretion rates, such as pancreatic cells or antibody-producing immune cells, typically have a very well-developed rough endoplasmic reticulum.",
